definition.value: A metabolite of finasteride.
An acyl-CoA(4-) resulting from the removal of all four protons from the phosphate and diphosphate groups of (25R)-3-oxocholest-4-en-26-oyl-CoA; major species at pH 7.3.
An acyl-CoA(4-) resulting from the removal of all four protons from the phosphate and diphosphate groups of (2R)-ibuprofenoyl-CoA; major species at pH 7.3.
An acyl-CoA(4-) resulting from the removal of all four protons from the phosphate and diphosphate groups of (2S)-ibuprofenoyl-CoA; major species at pH 7.3.
beta-D-Gal-(1->3)-{alpha-Neu5Ac-(2->3)-beta-D-Gal-(1->4)-[alpha-L-Fuc-(1->3)]-beta-D-GlcNAc-(1->6)}-D-GalNAc in which the anomeric configuration of the GalNAc residue at the reducing end is alpha.
A fatty acid-taurine conjugate derived from oleic acid.

A polyol marine coelenterate toxin composed of substituted N-3-hydroxypropyl-trans-3-amidoacrylamides and produced by species of Palythoa and Zoanthus soft corals (collectively called zoantharians), either as a defence mechanism or to assist them in capturing prey. An ionophore that forms cation channels through Na+/K+-ATPase, it is a potent vasoconstrictor useful in evaluation of anti-angina agents. It is considered to be one of the most poisonous non-protein substances known, second only to maitotoxin in terms of toxicity in mice.
Major species at pH 7.3
Major species at pH 7.3
Any member of the class of antibiotic polyketides originally isolated from the fungus Cylindrocladium ilicicola, isolated from the dead leaf of beach (Fagus sp.).
An organosulfonate oxoanion that is the conjugate base of tauroursocholic acid, obtained by the deprotonation of the sulfonic acid group. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3.

A carboxylic ester resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of hydroxy(diphenyl)acetic acid with the hydroxy group of (3-endo,8-syn)-8-(2-fluoroethyl)-3-hydroxy-8-methyl-8-azoniabicyclo[3.2.1]octane. Its bromide salt is used as a drug for the treatment asthma and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease.
A naphthalenesulfonic acid that is naphthalene-1-sulfonic acid which is substituted by tert-butyl groups at positions 2 and 6.
A member of the class of anthracenones that is 3,4-tetrahydroanthracen-1-one which is substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 2, 3, 6, 8 and 9, and a 2-oxopropyl group at position 3.
An enolate resulting from the deprotonation of the hydroxy group of the enol moiety of TAN-1612.

A 2-[benzyl(phenyl)amino]ethyl 5-(5,5-dimethyl-2-oxido-1,3,2-dioxaphosphinan-2-yl)-2,6-dimethyl-4-(3-nitrophenyl)-1,4-dihydropyridine-3-carboxylate that has (R)-configuration. It is a selective blocker of T-type Ca(2+) channels.

A 2-[benzyl(phenyl)amino]ethyl 5-(5,5-dimethyl-2-oxido-1,3,2-dioxaphosphinan-2-yl)-2,6-dimethyl-4-(3-nitrophenyl)-1,4-dihydropyridine-3-carboxylate that has (S)-configuration. It is a blocker of L- and T-type Ca(2+) channels.

A carboxylic ester resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of 5-(5,5-dimethyl-2-oxido-1,3,2-dioxaphosphinan-2-yl)-2,6-dimethyl-4-(3-nitrophenyl)-1,4-dihydropyridine-3-carboxylic acid with the hydroxy group of 2-[benzyl(phenyl)amino]ethanol.
A 1-(2-chlorophenyl)-2-isopropylaminoethanol that has (R)-configuration.
A  1-(2-chlorophenyl)-2-isopropylaminoethanol that has (S)-configuration.
A member of the class of monochlorobenzenes that is chlorobenzene which is substituted by a 1-hydroxy-2-[(propan-2-yl)amino]ethyl group at position 2.

A member of the class of thiadiazoles that is 1,3,4-thiadiazol-2-amine which is substituted by a (5-nitro-1,3-thiazol-2-yl)sulfanediyl group at position 5. It is a c-Jun N-terminal kinase inhibitor (IC50 = 0.7uM) and exhibits antibacterial properties.

An amino trisaccharide consisting of L-fucopyranosyl, D-galactopyranosyl and 2-acetamido-2-deoxy-D-glucopyranosyl residues joined in sequence by glycosidic bonds. The positions of attachement and the alpha/beta configuration of the linkages are unknown. In the structure shown, one of the R groups is an L-fucopyransyl-D-galactopyranosyl group; the remaining two R groups are hydrogens.
An ammonium ion derivative resulting from the protonation of the tertiary amino group of (-)-voacangine. The major species at pH 7.3.
A tertiary ammonium ion that is the conjugate acid of secodine, obtained by protonation of the nitrogen atom of the tetrahydropyridine moiety. The major microspecies at pH 7.3.
An ammonium ion derivative resulting from the protonation of the tertiary amino group of (-)-coronaridine.
An allotrope of carbon with molecular formula C18 existing as a ring of eighteen carbon atoms, connected by alternating triple and single bonds.

An organic anionic group obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate and carboxy functions as well as protonation of the amino function of N(1)-methyl-N(3)-[(3S)-3-amino-3-carboxypropyl]-pseudouridine 5'-phosphate residue; major species at 7.3.
A methyl ester resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of (5S,12bR,12cS)-7-carboxy-1-ethyl-3,6,8,12c-tetrahydro-4H-5,12b-ethanoindolo[3,2-a]quinolizin-5-ium with methanol.

An aminoheptasaccharide that is the MAN-3 glycan, alpha-D-Manp-(1->3)-[alpha-D-Manp-(1->6)]-beta-D-Manp-(1->4)-beta-D-GlcpNAc-(1->4)-D-GlcpNAc, in which the (1->6) linked mannosyl group has been glycosylated at positions 3 and 6 by alpha-D-mannopyranosyl groups.
A tertiary ammonium ion result from the protonation of the tertiary amino group of dehydrosecodine (the enamine form). An intermediate in the biosynthesis of aspidospermaand iboga alkaloids.
A tertiary ammonium ion resulting from the protonation of the tertiary amino group of 10-hydroxycoronaridine. The major species at pH 7.3.

A member of the class of pyrazoles that is 1H-pyrazole which is substituted by a 2,6-dichloro-4-(trifluoromethyl)phenyl, nitrile, (fluoromethyl)sulfanediyl and [(pyrazin-2-yl)methyl]nitrilo groups at positions 1,3,4 and 5, respectively. It is an experimental insecticide introduced by Nihon Nohyaku Co Ltd, Japan.
A racemate comprising equimolar amounts of (R)- and (S)-flufiprole. It is a phenylpyrazole insecticide used to control brown plant hopper and leafy beetle in rice.
A 1-[2,6-dichloro-4-(trifluoromethyl)phenyl]-5-[(2-methylprop-2-en-1-yl)amino]-4-[(trifluoromethyl)sulfinyl]-1H-pyrazole-3-carbonitrile that has R configuration at the sulfoxide.
A 1-[2,6-dichloro-4-(trifluoromethyl)phenyl]-5-[(2-methylprop-2-en-1-yl)amino]-4-[(trifluoromethyl)sulfinyl]-1H-pyrazole-3-carbonitrile that has S configuration at the sulfoxide.

A dibenzopyran that is Delta(9)-tetrahydrocannabinol which is lacking the hydroxy group and in which the pentyl group at position 3 has been replaced by a 1,1-dimethylbutyl group. A potent and highly selective CB2 receptor agonist.

A carbobicyclic compound that is bicyclo[3.1.1]hept-2-ene which is substituted by a hydroxymethyl group at position 2, a 2,6-dimethoxy-4-(2-methyloctan-2-yl)phenyl group at position 4, and two methyl groups at position 6 (the 1S,4S,5S stereoisomer). A highly selective and effective cannabinoid type-2 agonist and the enantiomer of HU-433.

A secondary carboxamide resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of 5-(4-chloro-3-methylphenyl)-1-(4-methylbenzyl)-1H-pyrazole-3-carboxylic acid with the amino group of (1S,2S,4R)-1,3,3-trimethylbicyclo[2.2.1]heptan-2-amine. A potent and selective cannabinoid receptor type 2 (CB2 receptor) inverse agonist (Ki = 0.6 nM).
A cannabinoid receptor agonist that binds to and activates type 2 cannabinoid receptors.

A member of the class of pyrazoles that is 1H-pyrazole that is substituted at positions 1, 3, 4, and 5 by 2,6-dichloro-4-(trifluoromethyl)phenyl, cyano, (trifluoromethyl)sulfinyl, and (2-methylprop-2-en-1-yl)nitrilo groups, respectively.
